PROGRAM_NAME: Smart Love Family Services - Clinical Services
AREASUPERVISION:
We model a supportive, collaborative, caregiving, and relational approach to supervision. To enhance caregiving to clients we model caregiving to staff. 
Ongoing supervision and support is an integral part of agency practice at SLFS because we highly value professional development as a lifelong process for psychotherapists. All therapists regardless of license and experience level receive one hour weekly individual supervision with a seasoned clinician. 
-The model is one that recognizes the value of therapists receiving ongoing care and support in their efforts to care for their clients. 
-Developmental process of learning to become the best therapist/caregiver possible and enjoying it! 
-Creates a positive, supportive community of learning together to achieve our ideals around how we want to care for people.

Supervision & Consultation Structure:
-At least one hour weekly individual supervision with a LCSW
-Student will bring in at least one process recording per week for supervision
-Regular meetings with administrative supervisor for help with administrative tasks
-Bi-monthly group case consultation with founder of Intrapsychic Humanism, Dr. Martha Heineman Pieper
-Weekly Clinical Training Seminar with Director of Training, Marian Sharkey, Ph.D., LCSW
-Weekly Parent Support Training Seminar led by staff parenting experts
-Monthly professional development support group
-Monthly Committee on Racial & Social Equity meetings
-Quarterly diversity trainings with outside experts
-Continuing education programs by Intrapsychic Humanism Society

PROGRAM_NAME: Administration for Children and Families, US Department of Health and Human Services

AREASUPERVISION:
My supervisory methodology is rooted in the person-centered, integrated developmental, and discrimination supervision models. The person-centered supervision model builds the supervisees self-confidence in the therapeutic relationship with their clients (Bernard & Goodyear, 2019). The integrated developmental model emphasizes the supervisee's consciousness, motivation, and self-reliance (Bernard & Goodyear, 2019). Finally, the discrimination model enables supervisees to attain an elevated level of proficiency within their counseling identity (Bornsheuer-Boswell et al., 2013). As supervisees grow more confident in their clinical abilities, the supervision model should also change to meet their needs.

Each supervisee is distinctive, and my goal is to help build their self-confidence to enhance their therapeutic relationships with clients. My goal is to strengthen their clinical skills until they reach competency in therapeutic interventions, assessment techniques, interpersonal assessment, client conceptualization, cultural competency, theoretical orientation, treatment planning, and ethics. While in a supervisory relationship, I will draw from teacher, consultant, and counselor roles from the discrimination model to assist with their present needs. In the teacher role, I will provide education based on the supervisee's learning style. In the counselor role, I will use counseling skills to understand and model behaviors and explore the supervisee's emotions related to transference and counter-transference. In the consultant role, I will collaborate with the supervisee to problem-solve the client's concerns.

AREASUPERVISION: Student interns will receive one hour per week individual supervision with LCSW

Interns receive weekly, reflective, individual supervision with an LCSW lasting no less than one hour. This is seen as protected time and is therefore consistent and reliable. Additional time is provided for logistical discussions and the supervisor is available for any urgent and/or emergency situations.

The supervisor and intern create a personalized learning plan which can include observations (of the intern or by the intern of other clinicians), co-facilitation, assigned related readings, and process recordings.

Interns also participate in group supervision with their cohort on a bi-weekly basis. This is a time to share best practices, collaborate, process challenging and growth experiences, and create a professional network of support and camaraderie.
